                <legend>&nbsp;Gutter Magic&nbsp;</legend>
                <div class="table" style="width: 100%; height: 100%">
                  <div style="height: 650px; padding-right: 5px; overflow: auto">
                    <div>Gutter magick is all about semiotics, tweaking reality with whatever is handy. Youre making connections between things that are, ostensibly, not related; manufacturing a limited coincidence. Its improv magick, and never works the same way twice. Just be careful; this stuff can mess you up if youre not prepared.</div>
                    <div style="margin: 8px 0 5px 0; font-weight: bold; border-bottom: 1px solid darkgray">Rolling Your Own</div>
                    <div>To build an effect, you need a set of symbolic elements. These are items that represent you and the target. They can be whatever makes sense, like old clothes, the targets diary, access to their iCloud account, etc. You also need something tied to the collective unconscious. This might be a movie where a man gets hit by a car, if youre trying to injure an enemy. A Raquel Welch <i></i>One Million Years B.C.</i> poster can help you break a friend out of jail. The utility of the object is irrelevant, its the symbolism that matters.</div>
                    <div style="margin-top: 6px">You need at least three items  though up to five is better, each in the following categories:</div>
                    <div style="margin: 5px 0 3px 0; display: grid; grid-template-columns: 160px auto; gap: 10px">
                      <div style="font-weight: 500">You</div>
                      <div>Your drivers license, your carnation from prom, your bronzed baby shoes, the current phone number of your first love.</div>
                      <div style="font-weight: 500">The Target</div>
                      <div>Their underpants, the date on which they lost their virginity, a sample of their DNA, a list of the last ten books they checked out from the library.</div>
                      <div style="font-weight: 500">The Collective Unconscious</div>
                      <div>A movie, a song, a pebble from the Berlin Wall, a first edition copy of The Great Gatsby, a Model T windshield, hair from Benedict Cumberbatchs shaving razor.</div>
                    </div>
                    <div>Once you have these assembled, you make up a ritual. It must make sense to you, and it should convince the cosmos that these disparate things are - at least temporarily - connected. The more items you have that relate to your goal, the more likely the spell is to succeed. The ritual can also be affected - positively or negatively by the quality of the components, the time that you spend on the ritual, or whether you perform it in a mystically potent place or at a cosmically significant time. You can also increase the chances of success by dropping aminor (+10) or significant (+20) charge in to the mix.</div>
                    <div style="margin: 8px 0 5px 0; font-weight: bold; border-bottom: 1px solid darkgray">So, What Can You Do With It?</div>
                    <div>You get to pick one of the following effects. Gutter magick is also sticky; i.e., it hangs around until the effect makes a difference. If the target succeeds despite it, or would have failed without it, it persists until its the deciding factor.</div>
                    <div style="margin: 5px 0 3px 0; display: grid; grid-template-columns: auto auto; gap: 10px 20px">
                      <div style="font-weight: 500">Bless</div>
                      <div>When you <i>Bless</i> an endeavor, you make it more likely to occur. This is using gutter magick at the appropriate scale to add to an objective. You perform your ritual and, if you succeed, get to puff up your objective.</div>
                      <div style="font-weight: 500">Bond</div>
                      <div>You form a symbolic <i>Bond</i> between yourself and someone else in the universe. Maybe you connect to an enemy, maybe the girl you have a crush on. Whats important is that due to the symbolism, when the cosmos looks upon you, you seem to be linked together. With a Bond, you get +10 when trying to explain something to, or cooperate with, the person to whom youre bonded. It lasts until it has made a difference.</div>
                      <div style="font-weight: 500">Boon</div>
                      <div>When you want something to go right, you can give a <i>Boon</i> to yourself or another. This grants +20 on a check relating to a specific condition which evokes the Boon. You cant just get a bonus to Notice, but you can get it when searching for fingerprints, or when you're trying to find Paula Rampling.</div>
                      <div style="font-weight: 500">Whammy</div>
                      <div>This redirects the inherent unfairness the cosmos toward a person or situation of your choice. This creates a -20 penalty to an opponents roll, and you must target this with exacting specificity. It cant just be the armored car guard, youre going to need a name and the conditions which evoke the effect.</div>
                      <div style="font-weight: 500">Curse</div>
                      <div>Maybe youd rather hurt someone than protect yourself from them. this effect employs synchronicity and coincidence to injure your target, pulling at the strands of fate to kick them in the astral nuts. It does 1d10 damage. Maybe theyre crossing a street and a car comes by and clips them. Maybe they break their nose opening the door to the office. They dont need to be anywhere near you - and its probably better that they arent - when the <i>Curse</i> manifests.</div>
